From db4d4b8a11e66e60272b0f44de2fd956f64ea005 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Francesco Pham <francesco.pham1@h-partners.com>
Date: Fri, 5 Jun 2026 19:25:31 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] memmgr: keep the SA published when HyperHold reclaim init
 fails
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

On devices whose kernel lacks the OHOS HyperHold/zswapd memcg extensions
(e.g. hybris_generic on the Volla X23 — OHOS on a Halium MT6789 5.10 kernel:
no /dev/memcg/memory.app_score, memory.zswapd_single_memcg_param), the
HyperHold-gated ReclaimStrategyManager::Init() fails. That made
MemMgrService::Init() return false, so OnStart() never Publish()ed the
Memory Manager system ability (MEMORY_MANAGER_SA_ID, 1909) even though the
memmgrservice process was running.

With SA 1909 absent, every GetSystemAbility(MEMORY_MANAGER_SA_ID) caller hit
the samgr GetSaWrap retry loop (RETRY_TIME_OUT_NUMBER=6 x SLEEP_INTERVAL_TIME
200ms = ~1.2s) before failing. The legacy window manager calls
MemMgrClient::OnWindowVisibilityChanged() on its single handler thread for
every window-visibility change, so each app transition blocked that thread
for ~1.2s, stalling the whole UI (deferred occlusion callbacks, system-bar
tint and post-animation layout).

Make the HyperHold ReclaimStrategyManager::Init() failure non-fatal: log a
warning and continue so the SA still publishes. ReclaimStrategyManager
self-guards every entry point on initialized_, so proactive reclaim is simply
inactive while the kernel-independent features (reclaim priority, low-memory
killer, window-visibility reporting) keep working.

Change-Id: I9f4fed848cbc778bea8938d00c4606a0555f8547
Signed-off-by: Francesco Pham <francesco.pham1@h-partners.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 services/memmgrservice/src/mem_mgr_service.cpp | 15 ++++++++++++---
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/services/memmgrservice/src/mem_mgr_service.cpp b/services/memmgrservice/src/mem_mgr_service.cpp
index 4e4e61d..987a56d 100644
--- a/services/memmgrservice/src/mem_mgr_service.cpp
+++ b/services/memmgrservice/src/mem_mgr_service.cpp
@@ -65,10 +65,19 @@ bool MemMgrService::Init()
     MultiAccountManager::GetInstance().Init();
 
 #ifdef USE_HYPERHOLD_MEMORY
-    // init reclaim strategy manager
+    // init reclaim strategy manager.
+    // hybris_generic: this device runs OHOS on a Halium kernel that lacks the OHOS
+    // HyperHold/zswapd memcg extensions (no /dev/memcg/memory.app_score,
+    // memory.zswapd_single_memcg_param), so ReclaimStrategyManager::Init() fails.
+    // Treat it as non-fatal so the memmgr SA still publishes: the manager self-guards
+    // every entry point on initialized_, and the kernel-independent features
+    // (reclaim-priority, low-memory-killer, window-visibility reporting) keep working.
+    // Without this, MemMgrService never Publish()es SA 1909, and every caller of
+    // GetSystemAbility(MEMORY_MANAGER_SA_ID) — notably WMS on every window-visibility
+    // change — burns ~1.2 s in the samgr GetSaWrap retry, stalling the whole UI.
     if (!ReclaimStrategyManager::GetInstance().Init()) {
-        HILOGE("ReclaimStrategyManager init failed");
-        return false;
+        HILOGW("ReclaimStrategyManager init failed; continuing with proactive reclaim "
+               "disabled (kernel lacks HyperHold memcg support)");
     }
 #endif
 
